<div id="co_document" class="co_document co_commentary co_commentaryEnhancement"><input alt="metadata" value="{ &quot;citations&quot;: {  }, &quot;pubs&quot;: {  } }" id="co_document_starPageMetadata" type="hidden"/><div><div class="co_cites">Multidistrict Lit Man Highlights</div><div class="co_contentBlock co_briefItState co_propBlock"><div class="co_publicationLine"><div class="co_headtext">Multidistrict Litigation Manual</div><span class="co_verticalDivider"> | </span><div class="co_date">May 2021 Update</div></div><div class="co_contentBlock co_briefItState co_authorLine"><span>David F. Herr<sup id="co_fnRef_I0b1e4c71abfe11eba0d9a2fb3da8ae81_N10034"><a class="co_footnoteReference" href="#co_footnote_I0b1e4c71abfe11eba0d9a2fb3da8ae81">a0</a></sup></span></div></div></div><div class="co_divider"/><div class="co_title"><div class="co_headtext">WHAT’S NEW 2021 Edition</div></div><?chunkMarker?><!--DHE--><div class="co_contentBlock x_introBlock"><div class="co_paragraph"><div class="co_paragraphText">This 2021 edition of the Multidistrict Litigation Manual brings this pathfinding work current on the many types of cases involved in multidistrict litigation. Most of the updated content comes in decisions from the Judicial Panel. The Panel’s approach to transfer decisions evolve every year, and these changes this year include:</div><ul class="co_customBulletList"><li><div class="co_paragraph co_indentHanging"><h2/><div class="co_paragraphText">• Analysis of dozens of additional Panel decisions</div></div></li><li><div class="co_paragraph co_indentHanging"><h2/><div class="co_paragraphText">• The Panel's adaptation to the 2020 pandemic, including the hearing of arguments remotely</div></div></li><li><div class="co_paragraph co_indentHanging"><h2/><div class="co_paragraphText">• Consideration of pandemic-related dockets, including insurance coverage cases and refund litigation</div></div></li><li><div class="co_paragraph co_indentHanging"><h2/><div class="co_paragraphText">• The Panel's increased focus on whether industry-wide centralization is feasible</div></div></li><li><div class="co_paragraph co_indentHanging"><h2/><div class="co_paragraphText">• A perceptible tendency of the Panel to assess if alternatives to transfer would better serve the purposes of efficient management of litigation, including scores of decisions where the Panel has articulated reasons for denying transfer (and hundreds of decisions and secondary authorities since the Federal Judicial Center revised the Manual in 2004)</div></div></li><li><div class="co_paragraph co_indentHanging"><h2/><div class="co_paragraphText">• A continued tendency of the Panel to explain its transfer decisions in terms of decisions in similar dockets in prior years</div></div></li><li><div class="co_paragraph co_indentHanging"><h2/><div class="co_paragraphText">• Elaboration on the Panel's concerns that transfer would, in some cases, increase the complexity of the litigation rather than ease it</div></div></li><li><div class="co_paragraph co_indentHanging"><h2/><div class="co_paragraphText">• Continuing recognition by the Panel that dockets where the same counsel appear in the cases are inherently less complex, and possibly less likely to be centralized</div></div></li><li><div class="co_paragraph co_indentHanging"><h2/><div class="co_paragraphText">• Considerations relating to selection of a transferee district and judge, including experience in similar cases, pendency of current and earlier cases, and even private practice experience of the judge</div></div></li><li><div class="co_paragraph co_indentHanging"><h2/><div class="co_paragraphText">• Analysis of decisions dealing with cases where arbitration agreements might remove cases from the courts</div></div></li></ul></div><div class="co_paragraph"><div class="co_paragraphText">The Panel continues to consider a wide variety of factors in deciding whether to transfer cases and where to transfer them, and several decisions illustrate the Panel’s willingness to transfer cases to experienced judges who have not presided or are not currently presiding over an MDL docket.</div></div><div class="co_paragraph"><div class="co_paragraphText">In many ways this Manual is a companion to the author’s Annotated Manual for Complex Litigation Fourth (Thomson Reuters, 2021 ed.). That work addresses in much greater detail the array of issues developed in complex litigation and brings the Federal Judicial Center’s 2004 publication up-to-date on developments in class action law, discovery, and case management in complex cases. Most of those developments relate directly to the management of cases transferred by the Panel.</div></div></div><div class="co_copyright">Westlaw. © 2021 Thomson Reuters. No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. Works.</div><div class="co_footnoteSection co_briefItState" id="co_footnoteSection"><h2 class="co_footnoteSectionTitle co_printHeading" id="co_footnoteSectionHeader">Footnotes</h2><div><div class="co_footnoteNumber"><span id="co_footnote_I0b1e4c71abfe11eba0d9a2fb3da8ae81"><a href="#co_fnRef_I0b1e4c71abfe11eba0d9a2fb3da8ae81_N10034">a0</a></span></div><div class="co_footnoteBody"><div class="co_paragraph"><div class="co_paragraphText">Maslon Edelman Borman &amp; Brand, LLP, Minneapolis, Minnesota.</div></div></div></div></div><table id="co_endOfDocument"><tr><td>End of Document</td><td class="co_endOfDocCopyright">© 2021 </td></tr></table></div>